comment:
Hear me out. 
I'm not denying that she's yikes, and totally understand why she has attracted so much negativity towards her. 
I just want people to remember that we're all humans and if somebody's been a bad person, it don't mean that they were born bad. There's reasoning behind why she has bad behaviour or bad morals or whatever it might be.
She's still human, and so are you, you know what pain feels like, and so does she. During your life time, you certainly had revelations about yourself. For example, realizing you've hurt people in the past: the wrong you've inflicted upon them, even if it was done unconciously, has inevitably bounced back to you, one way or another. 
Now the reason you're a better person today is because you realized deep down how much you cared about love in this world (everybody is born with this love in their heart), you've evolved and changed yourself through stages of understanding who you are and how you affect everything and everyone. And to this day, you're still evolving, you're still going through stages, you still make mistakes. You can sometimes get misleaded, but you manage to get back on the right path because the opportunity is not taken away from you. 
The thing is, some of us don't get all the opportunities to evolve. You can either let people have these opportunities or snatch'em away from them (that is a constant cycle of chaos that's going on in the world where people who have been consumed by negativity pass it on to their kids or from bully to victim, that's what I mean by snatching away people's opportunity to evolve). These "opportunities" often show up with time, but you can get robbed, figuratively speaking, and miss out on an opportunity to evolve. Who knows why she acts the way she acts (there are certainly parts of her life that could reveal the reasons, and only she can go back and process them, with the help of a pro.), the important thing is that she can change, but mental health can get in the way of that, especially if she receives hate from everywhere. 
You can certainly understand that sending negativity, or just being negative in regards to a person, is just as terrible as leaving a part of you behind.
If you don't get what I'm saying, imagine the idea that we all, humans, are the loneliest thing in the universe, and yet we were born together, on the same planet, so we could rely on each other, live, and strive as one in difficult times. We can't be letting each other down, whether one of us is acting wrong or not. We can't be perfect and that's fine, everyone has the potential to become a better person, and you have the power to do it with them. 
Now, is the negativity she manifested striking back at her? Absolutely. The problem isn't there though. You are feeding this bad energy by sending more negativity. 
If we could, instead of hating on a person for her wrongdoings, acknowledge that she's just another lost soul like the rest of us, walking a path that's different in layout, but similar in destination, we'd be far more happier, simply because we would all get closer and not feel so disassociated from life.
Instead, we detach ourselves from people cause our ego tells us we're better than "that person".
This world is confusing and it's inevitable for us, at one point or another, to get caught in the fog, we need to realize that and protect each other from the confusion that's consuming us. 
We are blinded by this form of entertainment that's brought to us through other's people suffering. In fact, so blinded that we actually start hurting ourselves, and putting our hands in the middle of all the mess and adding negativity into the mix. 
We're a family, we're all linked by the strangeness of the universe, we can't be mad at that, we should be relieved. There's no enemies until you create them. 
I just wish situation like these didn't end up with one person being left behind for her wrongdoings. We all should be supportive of one another (doesn't mean supporting the wrongful acts, but the good that can be found deep down in a person), and give everyone a chance to become good and find happiness.

comment:
Loooooong before this whole Johnny Depp situation I already had this awful feeling about her. I am on the autistic spectrum and for some reason I have this strange 6th sense in telling when people are bad. 

My sister got into an abusive relationship with a man last year, and everyone in my family thought this guy was amazing. But I knew from the get-go that he was a monster. I hated him from the moment we met. It was like every time I saw him a fire lit in the pit of my stomach. My family told me I was wrong and to stop being so judgmental, and I just didn't get WHY no body saw that he was completely deceptive.

One night during dinner I apparently touched the wrong nerve and he showed his true colors. He went from being his 'perfect' self to doing a 180 into a complete rage. That's when everyone saw that he was a complete psychopath. After that event over dinner, he had apparently flipped out at my sister behind closed doors. The next day when he was at work she came to me, my boyfriend and my parents and told us what was happening behind the scenes and asked us to help her get out.  

I had that exact feeling when I first saw Amber Heard. I knew she was an abhorrent human being when I first put eyes on her. The funny thing is, it all made sense to me when the abuse allegations came out. These people are the absolute scum of the earth. I hope she gets what she deserves.
